# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bakkwa
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bakkwa/a-gei] The ageh was reportedly created in 1965 by Iông-tēⁿ Gím-bûn (楊鄭錦文), who combined various food items sold at her Chin-lí street (真理街) food stall to sell as a new food item.
[src:bakkwa/a-gei] This original ageh consisted of fried tofu that has been emptied of its center, stuffed with cellophane noodles cooked in stewed ground pork, its opening sealed and covered with a carrot and surimi mixture, and then steamed to completion.
[src:bakkwa/a-gei] The dish incorporates several techniques from other dishes, including the stuffing of abura-age in the manner of *inarizushi*, the capping of tofu with surimi to make Yong Tau Foo, and the use of cellophane noodles as a filling for many stuffed pastries.
[src:bakkwa/a-gei] The individual a-gei are served with either a plain soy-based or a sweet chili sauce.
[src:bakkwa/a-gei] A-gei is commonly eaten with a bowl of stuffed fish ball soup in the winter and a glass of cold soy milk in the summer.
[src:bakkwa/acar] Through examining the etymology, the similar sounding name strongly suggests that indeed acar was derived from the Indian achar pickle.
[src:bakkwa/acar] Indian achar was transmitted in antiquity to the maritime realm of Southeast Asia, which today is recognized as acar in Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore and Brunei, and then on to the Philippines as *atchara*.
[src:bakkwa/acar] The adoption of this vegetable pickling technique possibly took place during the Srivijaya period between 7th to 13th century.
[src:bakkwa/acar] British navigator Thomas Forrest wrote that acar made of salted limes and palm vinegar was often of use to Coromandel Muslim sailors (*Chulias*) to prevent scurvy and was sold as far as Aceh.
[src:bakkwa/acar] The Southeast Asian variations are usually made from different vegetables such as cucumber, carrots, cabbage, shallot, bird's eye chili and yardlong beans, which are pickled in vinegar, sometimes with kaffir lime to add citrus aroma, and also dried chillies.
[src:bakkwa/acar] Some recipes might have the vegetables tossed in ground peanuts.
[src:bakkwa/acar] *Acar* is commonly served as a condiment to be eaten with a main course, such as *martabak*, *nasi goreng* (fried rice), satay, and almost all varieties of *soto*.
[src:bakkwa/acar] Just like common pickles, the sour taste of *acar* is meant to freshen up a meal, especially fishy dishes such as *ikan bakar* (grilled fish) or rich and oily dishes such as mutton satay to neutralize the fat.
[src:bakkwa/acar] In Indonesia, acar is commonly made from small chunks of cucumber, carrot, shallot, bird's eye chili and occasionally pineapple, and marinated in a sweet and sour solution of sugar and vinegar.
[src:bakkwa/acar] Some households add lemongrass or ginger to spice it up.
[src:bakkwa/acar] It is usually used as condiment to accompany grilled foods such as satay.
[src:bakkwa/acar] Nevertheless, *acar* can also be consumed as a whole, complete dish.
[src:bakkwa/acar] For example, *ikan acar kuning* is a fish dish (gourami, mackerel or tilapia) served in *acar* pickles of cucumber, carrot, shallot and red chili, mixed with yellow spice paste made of ground turmeric, candlenut, ginger, garlic and shallot.
[src:bakkwa/acar] It is known as *atjar* (pickle) in Dutch cuisine, derived from Indonesian *acar*, since the Netherlands and Indonesia share colonial ties.
[src:bakkwa/acar] Variations of Malaysian and Singaporean *acar* include *acar awak* or Nyonya *acar* and Malay *acar*.
[src:bakkwa/acar] *Acar awak* is more elaborate, containing additional vegetables such as eggplants as well as aromatic spices in the pickling mix.
[src:bakkwa/acar] The salad has also been adopted into Thai cuisine, where it is called *achat* (Thai: อาจาด, pronounced [ʔāː.t͡ɕàːt]).
[src:bakkwa/acar] It is made with cucumber, red chilies, red onions or shallots, vinegar, sugar and salt.
[src:bakkwa/acar] It is served as a side dish with the Thai version of satay (Thai: สะเต๊ะ).
[src:bakkwa/acar] With Indian and Malay slaves initially brought by the British Empire, *atchar* became a favourite condiment in South Africa.
[src:bakkwa/acar] The local variation is usually made with green mangoes.
[src:bakkwa/acehnese-cuisine] A variety of Acehnese food is cooked with curry or coconut milk, which is generally combined with meat such as buffalo, beef, goat meat, lamb, mutton, fish, or chicken.
[src:bakkwa/acehnese-cuisine] Several Aceh dishes can trace their origins to India, such as roti canai, which was derived from Indian flatbread.
[src:bakkwa/adhirasam] Adhirasam is a popular as an offering to the relatives during Deepavali and Ganesha Chaturthi festivals, both at home and in temples in Tamil Nadu and Karnataka.
[src:bakkwa/adhirasam] The earliest documented references to Adhirasam emerge from medieval Tamil kingdoms, particularly the Chola dynasty, where it appeared as a favored item in royal feasts and temple rituals.
[src:bakkwa/adhirasam] According to inscriptions from the 16th century, during the reign of Vijayanagara emperor Krishnadevaraya, the sweet was made from rice flour, jaggery, ghee and pepper.
[src:bakkwa/adhirasam] At the annual festival at the Panchavarnesvar Temple in Thirunallur (located near Kumbakonam, Tamil Nadu), an offering of 6000 Adhirasams along with 6000 vadas is made to the Gods; the entire lot is cooked in the temple kitchen between sunrise and 11 pm, for the prayers that take place at midnight.
[src:bakkwa/adhirasam] It is a popular Deepavali sweet preparation for Tamil people.
[src:bakkwa/adhirasam] The authentic preparation takes about a week.
[src:bakkwa/adhirasam] First the rice is soaked in water and dried in shade and ground into a fine powder when the rice is 3/4th dried and retains some moisture.
[src:bakkwa/adhirasam] For adding sweet "vellam" (jaggery in Tamil) is melted in water by boiling it till it reaches soft-ball consistency (235–240 °F (113–116 °C), if using a candy thermometer) and added to the rice flour along with some powdered cardamom to make a thick dough.
[src:bakkwa/adhirasam] It is then transferred to an earthenware pot and the top of the pot is closed with a thin white cloth.
[src:bakkwa/adhirasam] It is then allowed to ferment for about 3–5 days by placing it in the sunlight during the day.
[src:bakkwa/adhirasam] Finally, when the batter is ready for preparation, small balls of the dough is taken and flattened using fingers in a small piece of oil-brushed banana leaf and deep fried in oil until golden brown.
[src:bakkwa/adhirasam] Then it is pressed with a flat bottomed bowl to remove the excess oil.
[src:bakkwa/agar] As found in nature, agar is a mixture of two components, the linear polysaccharide agarose and a heterogeneous mixture of smaller molecules called agaropectin.
[src:bakkwa/agar] It forms the supporting structure in the cell walls of certain species of algae, and is released on boiling.
[src:bakkwa/agar] The processing of food-grade agar removes the agaropectin, and the commercial product is essentially pure agarose.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Agar has been used as an ingredient in desserts throughout Asia and also as a solid substrate to contain culture media for microbiological work.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Agar can be used as a laxative; an appetite suppressant; a vegan substitute for gelatin; a thickener for soups; in fruit preserves, ice cream, and other desserts; as a clarifying agent in brewing; and for sizing paper and fabrics.
[src:bakkwa/agar] The word *agar* comes from **agar-agar**, the Malay name for red algae (*Gigartina*, *Eucheuma*, *Gracilaria*) from which the jelly is produced.
[src:bakkwa/agar] It is also known as **kanten** (Japanese: 寒天) (from the phrase ***kan**-zarashi tokoro**ten*** (寒晒し心太) or "cold-exposed agar"), **Japanese isinglass**, **China grass**, **Ceylon moss**, and **Jaffna moss**.
[src:bakkwa/agar] *Gracilaria edulis* or its synonym *G. lichenoides* is specifically referred to as **agal-agal** or **Ceylon agar**.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Macroalgae have been used widely as food by coastal cultures, especially in Southeast Asia.
[src:bakkwa/agar] In the Philippines, *Gracilaria*, known as *gulaman* (also *guraman*, *gar-garao*, or *gulaman dagat*, among other names) in Tagalog, have been harvested and used as food for centuries, eaten both fresh or sun-dried and turned into jellies.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Carrageenan, derived from gusô (*Eucheuma* spp.), which also congeals into a gel-like texture is also used similarly among the Visayan peoples and have been recorded in the even earlier *Diccionario De La Lengua Bisaya, Hiligueina y Haraia de la isla de Panay y Sugbu y para las demas islas* (c.
[src:bakkwa/agar] 1637) of the Augustinian missionary Alonso de Méntrida (in Spanish).
[src:bakkwa/agar] In the book, Méntrida describes gusô as being cooked until it melts, and then allowed to congeal into a sour dish.
[src:bakkwa/agar] In Ambon Island in the Maluku Islands of Indonesia, agar is extracted from *Graciliaria* and eaten as a type of pickle or a sauce.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Jelly seaweeds were also favoured and foraged by Malay communities living on the coasts of the Riau Archipelago and Singapore in Southeast Asia for centuries.
[src:bakkwa/agar] 19th century records indicate that dried *Graciliaria* were one of the bulk exports of British Malaya to China.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Poultices made from agar were also used for swollen knee joints and sores in Johore and Singapore.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Agar normally solidifies at room temperature without the need to freeze.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Agar was first subjected to chemical analysis in 1859 by the French chemist Anselme Payen, who had obtained agar from the marine algae *Gelidium corneum*.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Beginning in the late 19th century, agar began to be used as a solid medium for growing various microbes.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Agar was first described for use in microbiology in 1882 by the German microbiologist Walther Hesse, an assistant working in Robert Koch's laboratory, on the suggestion of his wife Fanny Hesse.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Agar quickly supplanted gelatin as the base of microbiological media, due to its higher melting temperature, allowing microbes to be grown at higher temperatures without the media liquefying.
[src:bakkwa/agar] With its newfound use in microbiology, agar production quickly increased.
[src:bakkwa/agar] This production centered on Japan, which produced most of the world's agar until World War II.
[src:bakkwa/agar] However, with the outbreak of World War II, many nations were forced to establish domestic agar industries in order to continue microbiological research.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Around the time of World War II, approximately 2,500 tons of agar were produced annually.
[src:bakkwa/agar] By the mid-1970s, production worldwide had increased dramatically to approximately 10,000 tons each year.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Since then, production of agar has fluctuated due to unstable and sometimes over-utilized seaweed populations.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Agar consists of a mixture of two polysaccharides: agarose and agaropectin.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Agarose constitutes about 70% of the mixture, while agaropectin constitutes about 30% of it.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Agarose is a linear polymer made up of repeating units of agarobiose, a disaccharide made up of D-galactose and 3,6-anhydro-L-galactopyranose.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Agaropectin is a heterogeneous mixture of smaller molecules that occur in lesser amounts, and is made up of alternating units of D-galactose and L-galactose heavily modified with acidic side-groups, such as sulfate, glucuronate, and pyruvate.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Agar exhibits a phenomenon known as hysteresis whereby, when mixed with water, it solidifies and forms a gel below about 32–42 °C (305–315 K; 90–108 °F), which is called the gel point, and melts above 85 °C (358 K; 185 °F), which is the melting point.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Hysteresis is the property of having a difference between the gel point and melting point temperatures.
[src:bakkwa/agar] This property lends a suitable balance between easy melting and good gel stability at relatively high temperatures.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Since many scientific applications require incubation at temperatures close to human body temperature (37 °C), agar is more appropriate than other solidifying agents that melt at this temperature, such as gelatin.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Agar-agar is a natural vegetable gelatin counterpart.
[src:bakkwa/agar] It is white and semi-translucent when sold in packages as washed and dried strips or in powdered form.
[src:bakkwa/agar] It can be used to make jellies, puddings, and custards.
[src:bakkwa/agar] When making jelly, it is boiled in water until the solids dissolve.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Sweetener, flavoring, coloring, fruits and or vegetables are then added, and the liquid is poured into molds to be served as desserts and vegetable aspics or incorporated with other desserts such as a layer of jelly in a cake.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Agar-agar is approximately 80% dietary fiber, so it can serve as an intestinal regulator.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Its bulking quality has been behind fad diets in Asia, for example the *kanten* (the Japanese word for agar-agar) diet.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Once ingested, *kanten* triples in size and absorbs water.
[src:bakkwa/agar] This results in the consumers feeling fuller.
[src:bakkwa/agar] One use of agar in Japanese cuisine is in *anmitsu*, a dessert made of small cubes of agar jelly and served in a bowl with various fruits or other ingredients.
[src:bakkwa/agar] It is also the main ingredient in *mizu yōkan*, another popular Japanese food.
[src:bakkwa/agar] In Philippine cuisine, it is used to make the jelly bars in the various gulaman refreshments like *sago't gulaman*, *samalamig*, or desserts such as *buko pandan*, *agar flan*, *halo-halo*, *fruit cocktail jelly*, and the black and red *gulaman* used in various fruit salads.
[src:bakkwa/agar] In Vietnamese cuisine, jellies made of flavored layers of agar-agar, called *thạch*, are a popular dessert, and are often made in ornate molds for special occasions.
[src:bakkwa/agar] In Indian cuisine, agar is used for making desserts.
[src:bakkwa/agar] In Burmese cuisine, a sweet jelly known as *kyauk kyaw* is made from agar.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Agar jelly is widely used in Taiwanese bubble tea.
[src:bakkwa/agar] It can be used as addition to (or as a replacement for) pectin in jelly, jam, or marmalade, as a substitute to gelatin for its superior gelling properties, and as a strengthening ingredient in souffles and custards.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Another use of agar-agar is in a Russian dish *ptich'ye moloko* (bird's milk), a rich jellified custard (or soft meringue) used as a cake filling or chocolate-glazed as individual sweets.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Agar-agar may also be used as the gelling agent in gel clarification, a culinary technique used to clarify stocks, sauces, and other liquids.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Mexico has traditional candies made out of Agar gelatin, most of them in colorful, half-circle shapes that resemble a melon or watermelon fruit slice, and commonly covered with sugar.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Agar-agar is an allowed nonorganic/nonsynthetic additive used as a thickener, gelling agent, texturizer, moisturizer, emulsifier, flavor enhancer, and absorbent in certified organic foods.
[src:bakkwa/agar] An agar plate or Petri dish is used to provide a growth medium using a mix of agar and other nutrients in which microorganisms, including bacteria and fungi, can be cultured and observed under the microscope.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Agar is indigestible for many organisms so that microbial growth does not affect the gel used and it remains stable.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Agar is typically sold commercially as a powder that can be mixed with water and prepared similarly to gelatin before use as a growth medium.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Nutrients are typically added to meet the nutritional needs of the microbes organism, the formulations of which may be "undefined" where the precise composition is unknown, or "defined" where the exact chemical composition is known.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Agar is often dispensed using a sterile media dispenser.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Different algae produce various types of agar.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Each agar has unique properties that suit different purposes.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Because of the agarose component, the agar solidifies.
[src:bakkwa/agar] When heated, agarose has the potential to melt and then solidify.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Because of this property, they are referred to as "physical gels".
[src:bakkwa/agar] In contrast, polyacrylamide polymerization is an irreversible process, and the resulting products are known as chemical gels.
[src:bakkwa/agar] There are a variety of different types of agar that support the growth of different microorganisms.
[src:bakkwa/agar] A nutrient agar may be permissive, allowing for the cultivation of any non-fastidious microorganisms; a commonly used nutrient agar for bacteria is the Luria Bertani (LB) agar which contains lysogeny broth, a nutrient-rich medium used for bacterial growth.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Additionally, 2216 Marine Broth (MB) agar, with high salt content, is optimized for growing heterotrophic marine bacteria like those of the *Vibrio* genus, while Terrific Broth (TB) agar is used to non-selectively culture high yields of the bacterium *E. coli*.
[src:bakkwa/agar] More generally, enriched media is an agar variety that is infused with the necessary nutrients required by fastidious organisms to grow.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Despite the large diversity of agar mediums, yeast extract is a common ingredient across all varieties as it is a macronutrient that provides a nitrogen source for all bacterial cell types.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Other fastidious organisms may require the addition of different biological fluids such as horse or sheep blood, serum, egg yolk, and so on.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Agar plates can also be selective, and can be used to promote the growth of bacteria of interest while inhibiting others.
[src:bakkwa/agar] A variety of chemicals may be added to create an environment favourable for specific types of bacteria or bacteria with certain properties, but not conducive for growth of others.
[src:bakkwa/agar] For example, antibiotics may be added in cloning experiments whereby bacteria with antibiotic-resistant plasmid are selected.
[src:bakkwa/agar] In addition to antibiotic treated agar, other selective and indicator agar plates include TCBS agar and MacConkey agar.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Thiosulfate citrate bile salts sucrose (TCBS) agar is used to differentiate Vibrio species based on their sucrose metabolism, since only some will metabolize the sucrose in the plate and change its pH.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Indicator dyes included in the gel will display a visual change of the pH by changing the gel color from green to yellow.
[src:bakkwa/agar] MacConkey agar contains bile salts and crystal violet to selectively grow gram-negative bacteria and differentiate between species using pH-indicator dyes that demonstrate lactose metabolism properties.
[src:bakkwa/agar] As a gel, an agar or agarose medium is porous and therefore can be used to measure microorganism motility and mobility.
[src:bakkwa/agar] The gel's porosity is directly related to the concentration of agarose in the medium, so various levels of effective viscosity (from the cell's "point of view") can be selected, depending on the experimental objectives.
[src:bakkwa/agar] A common identification assay involves culturing a sample of the organism deep within a block of nutrient agar.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Cells will attempt to grow within the gel structure.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Motile species will be able to migrate, albeit slowly, throughout the gel, and infiltration rates can then be visualized, whereas non-motile species will show growth only along the now-empty path introduced by the invasive initial sample deposition.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Another setup commonly used for measuring chemotaxis and chemokinesis utilizes the under-agarose cell migration assay, whereby a layer of agarose gel is placed between a cell population and a chemoattractant.
[src:bakkwa/agar] As a concentration gradient develops from the diffusion of the chemoattractant into the gel, various cell populations requiring different stimulation levels to migrate can then be visualized over time using microphotography as they tunnel upward through the gel against gravity along the gradient.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Research grade agar is used extensively in plant biology as it is optionally supplemented with a nutrient and/or vitamin mixture that allows for seedling germination in Petri dishes under sterile conditions (given that the seeds are sterilized as well).
[src:bakkwa/agar] Nutrient and/or vitamin supplementation for *Arabidopsis thaliana* is standard across most experimental conditions.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Murashige & Skoog (MS) nutrient mix and Gamborg's B5 vitamin mix in general are used.
[src:bakkwa/agar] A 1.0% agar/0.44% MS+vitamin dH2O solution is suitable for growth media between normal growth temps.
[src:bakkwa/agar] When using agar, within any growth medium, it is important to know that the solidification of the agar is pH-dependent.
[src:bakkwa/agar] The optimal range for solidification is between 5.4 and 5.7.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Usually, the application of potassium hydroxide is needed to increase the pH to this range.
[src:bakkwa/agar] A general guideline is about 600 μl 0.1M KOH per 250 ml GM.
[src:bakkwa/agar] This entire mixture can be sterilized using the liquid cycle of an autoclave.
[src:bakkwa/agar] This hormone/GM solution can be spread across the surface of Petri dishes sown with germinated and/or etiolated seedlings.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Experiments with the moss *Physcomitrella patens*, however, have shown that choice of the gelling agent – agar or Gelrite – does influence phytohormone sensitivity of the plant cell culture.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Gelidium agar is used primarily for bacteriological plates.
[src:bakkwa/agar] Gracilaria agar is used mainly in food applications.
[src:bakkwa/agar] In 2016, AMAM, a Japanese company, developed a prototype for agar-based commercial packaging system called Agar Plasticity, intended as a replacement for oil-based plastic packaging.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Agriculture is one of the main industries in Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] It contributes to the food security, rural development and conservation of Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Around 24% of Taiwan's land is used for farming.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan is a global leader in vertical farming and agritourism.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Agriculture has been an important sector of Taiwanese life since ages ago.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] From archaeological sites in Changbin Township, Taitung County, since Paleolithic Age around 30,000-50,000 years ago, people hunted, fished and gathered.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Only in the Neolithic Age around 5,000-2,000 years ago, did people began to live their sedentary lifestyle where they grew rice and other crops and domesticated animals.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] During the Iron Age around 2,000 years ago, people in the northern coast of Taiwan began to make iron tools and food production increased significantly.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In the 17th century, people from China began to migrate to Taiwan where they fished, hunted and grew crops.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Most of them settled in the area around Tainan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] During the Dutch Formosa in the early 17th century, the Dutch promoted the production of sugarcane and rice.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] At that time, 119 km2 of cultivated land in Taiwan belonged to the Dutch East India Company.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The Dutch exported Taiwan's agricultural products and imported peas, tomatoes, wax apples and mangoes from Southeast Asia and United States to Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The Dutch introduced the domestic turkey to Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] During the rule of Koxinga in the Kingdom of Tungning in the late 17th century, the number of immigrants from China to Taiwan increased to 200,000 people.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] This resulted in the increase of land under cultivation to 292 km2.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Koxinga established a land tenure system and taught people to build reservoirs for irrigation.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Chinese people also brought 43 kinds of vegetable from South China, such as leeks, garlic and Chinese cabbage.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] During the Qing Dynasty, immigration from Mainland China to Taiwan increased because of wars and famines in the mainland.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] People began to build canals for irrigation.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] At this time, the cultivated land in Taiwan increased to 3,506 km2 by 1895.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The eighteen century official Chiang Yun-chuan was responsible for significant improvements in irrigation and flood control in southern Taiwan and was incorporated into the local folk religion as a deity.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] During the Empire of Japan, the Japanese greatly improved the agriculture sectors in Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] They built concrete dams, reservoirs and aqueducts which forms an extensive irrigation system, such as the Chianan Irrigation.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Arable land for rice and sugarcane productions increased by more than 74% and 30% respectively.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] They also established farmers' associations.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Agriculture sector dominated the economy of Taiwan at that time.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 1904, 23% area of Taiwan was used as agricultural land.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The Taiwan Agricultural Research institute (TARI) was founded in 1895 by the Japanese colonial powers.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] By 1939 Taiwan was the third largest exporter of bananas and canned pineapple in the world.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] After the handover of Taiwan from Japan to the Republic of China in 1945, the government revitalized the agricultural sector first to recover from the damage caused by World War II and completed a full recovery by 1953.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In the early 1950s, agriculture was Taiwan's largest economic sector and the vast majority of Taiwanese were farmers.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The government extended agricultural facilities and introduced the land reform program under the Sino-American Joint Commission on Rural Reconstruction.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] By 1956, agricultural land accounted for 34% of Taiwan's land use.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 1958, horticulturalist Cheng Chao-hsiung launched an experimental farm for deciduous fruit in the Central Mountain Range.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Aided by veterans of the Chinese Civil War moving to the region, larger scale production of apples, peaches and plums began the following decade and continued to 1979.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In the late 1940s, Taiwan underwent high-speed economic growth and industrialization.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 1963, industrial sectors output value exceeded agricultural sectors output value.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] However, this caused pressure on the agricultural sector as more and more people moved away from rural areas and labor costs increased.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In the 1970s, the role of agriculture shifted from the primary focus of the economy to a supporting role.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The government at that time issued policies for farmers to grow organic crops.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In the 1980s, much farmland was left idle due to the emigration of people from rural to urban areas as well as Taiwan beginning to open up to staple food imports.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] On 1 January 2002, Taiwan joined the World Trade Organization under the name Separate Customs Territory of Taiwan, Penghu, Kinmen and Matsu.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] This accession caused further damage to the agricultural sector in Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In response, the government has promoted agricultural tourism.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] President Lee Teng-hui believed that agriculture was the backbone of a nation and promoted it extensively.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] He implemented health insurance and occupational hazard insurance programs for farmers.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] He also emphasized the Japanese roots of much of Taiwan's agricultural infrastructure.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] While the importance of agriculture to the Taiwanese economy has declined greatly from its heyday Taiwan has become a global leader in the vertical farming industry.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Due to their efficient development of vertical farming technology and know-how Taiwanese firms are often partnered with by international firms looking to start vertical farming ventures in their home countries.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The vertical farming industry benefits from the high concentration of LED, robotics, engineering, and data processing firms in Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Vertical farms in Taiwan primarily compete with imported produce and focus on producing premium vegetables as their products remain more expensive than those from Taiwan's traditional farms.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Recently, the government has introduced new policy to reactivate all of the remaining idle farmland to ensure food security, food self-sufficiency and to revitalize the agriculture sectors.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Policies to develop the sector to be more competitive, modern and green were also introduced.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] This has led to a large number of urban youth taking up farming.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Since 2009 the Agriculture Council has subsidized education and training for new farmers, most of whom already hold advanced degrees.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2020 the Taiwanese government's Council of Agriculture set aside NT$5 billion (US$166.21 million) in loans for produce, livestock and aquaculture operations as well as other agriculture-based enterprises effected by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The loans are at a preferential rate of 0.79 percent to 1.68 percent.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2021 the Taiwanese government began incentivizing rice farmers to diversify their production beyond the staple crop.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan's agriculture industry now satisfies 90% of its domestic demand, making it a model of self-sufficiency.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Agriculture-related affairs in Taiwan are handled by the Ministry of Agriculture (MOA), headed by Minister Chen Junne-jih, and its division Agriculture and Food Agency.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan houses the headquarters of the World Vegetable Center.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan is also a member of world organizations related to agriculture, such as the African-Asian Rural Development Organization, Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, International Commission for the Conservation of Atlantic Tunas and World Trade Organization.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Agriculture in Taiwan consists of four sectors, with crops (47.39%), livestock (37%), fishery (15.58%) and forestry (0.03%) accounting for total agricultural output of NT$580 billion in 2023.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2023, Taiwan harvested 1.46 million tons of paddy rice from 222,413 hectares of land, for a yield of 6,566 kg per hectare and a total value of NT$34.9 billion.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] It is the most important cash crop in Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The quality of Taiwanese rice is extremely high.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Before the Japanese colonial period, most rice grown in Taiwan was long-grained Indica rice.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The Japanese introduced short-grained Japonica into Taiwan, which quickly changed both the farming and eating patterns of the Taiwanese.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2023, Taiwan harvested 92,467 tonnes of betel nuts from 37,293 hectares of land, the second most valuable cash crop after rice.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Cocoa cultivation on Taiwan began during the Japanese period but support ended after World War II.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The next wave of cultivation occurred in the 1970s but petered out because farmers lacked the expertise necessary to process the raw beans.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The modern industry was kickstarted by Chiu Ming-sung, a betel nut farmer and chocolatier from Pingtung who in 2007 became the first in Taiwan to make tree-to-bar chocolate.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan's cocoa production is centered in Pingtung in Southern Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Because of high production costs and small farm size, Taiwanese cocoa producers focus on producing estate-grade beans.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In Pingtung county cocoa is generally grown as a companion crop to betel nut as the tall betel nut palms shade the cocoa plants.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] As of 2020 approximately 200-300 acres was under cultivation in Pingtung supporting around 30 chocolate making companies.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The cocoa industry supports a significant domestic cocoa processing and chocolate making industry.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan is one of the few mature chocolate making countries to also be a cocoa producer.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2021 Taiwan tightened the labelling regulations for chocolate.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The first coffee plants on Taiwan were imported by the British to Tainan in 1884 with the first significant small scale cultivation taking place in New Taipei City's Sanxia District.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Tainan remains the heart of Taiwanese coffee culture.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Commercial coffee production in Taiwan began during the Japanese colonial period.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The Japanese developed the industry to feed the export market.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Production reached a peak in 1941 following the introduction of arabica coffee plants.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Production declined shortly thereafter as a result of World War II.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Domestic production is small—at 856 tons in 2023—but of high quality.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Imported beans account for the vast majority of coffee sold in Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The coffee borer beetle is a significant pest in Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] 1 is the first popular domestically bred coffee cultivar.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] It can be grown at lower altitudes than most coffee varieties and produces excellent quality beans.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2023, Taiwan harvested 2.4 million tonnes of fruits from 173,766 hectares of land with a total value of NT$95.8 billion.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan's fruit crops include banana, grape, guava, jujube, lychee, mandarin orange, mango, orange, papaya, pineapple, pomelo, sand pear, dragon fruit, starfruit, strawberry, watermelon and wax apple.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The annual fruits export is 60,000 tons with a value of NT$3,452 million.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2018 the largest export market of Taiwanese fruits was China.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2022 the largest export market of Taiwanese fruits was Japan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Most avocado varieties grown in Taiwan produce large fruit.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Domestic avocados compete with imported American hass avocados in the local market.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Cultivation grew from 506 hectares in 2011 to 1,149 hectares in 2020 due to rising popularity.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Bananas are Taiwan's most important export fruit.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The Taiwan Banana Research Institute is tasked to undergo research and development of banana cultivation in Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] By 1984 there were 34,000 hectares of citrus orchards in Taiwan annual yields of 360,000 metric tons with mandarin oranges and tangerines leading in production.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2008 a glut in orange production forced the export of surplus fruit to China.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] President Ma Ying-jeou even personally contributing $80,000 NTD to support an orchard in Gukeng township in Yunlin County as a result of the glut.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The average pomelo harvest is 74,000 tonnes.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Pomelos are exported to China and Japan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Greenpeace has warned that global warming could negatively impact Taiwanese pomelo production.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2018 there were 2,737 hectares of lemons in cultivation with 1,820 of those located in Pingtung County.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan produces a small amount of Australian finger lime.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2022 China blocked the importation of Taiwanese citrus due to tensions over the 2022 visit by Nancy Pelosi to Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] This affected the pomelo industry in particular due to the ban's timing and its exposure to the Chinese market.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Production of custard apples in concentrated in Taitung County, Kaohsiung, and Pingtung County.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Annual production is 57,000 metric tons.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Historically, 23% of production was exported to China, but Chinese authorities banned new imports of Taiwanese custard apples in 2021.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Pingtung is the center of dragonfruit cultivation which is known locally as pitaya.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Academic Yen Chung-Ruey is known as Taiwan's “Father of Pitaya.” Most of the production is consumed domestically but dragonfruit are also exported to Canada, China and Hong Kong.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Guavas are a significant product with a little over half of exports going to Canada, in 2019 Taiwan received permission to export guavas to the United States for the first time.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Mangos have been cultivated in Taiwan for more than 400 years.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] For the last fifty years the market has been dominated by the Irwin mango.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The Irwin mango was first grown in Taiwan in 1962 by Cheng Han-chih (鄭罕池) in Douliuzai Village, Yujing District, Tainan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 1973 the government designated Douliuzai Village as a mango special agricultural zone.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] By the 1970s the residents of Douliuzai Village were known for their wealth due to mango cultivation.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Cheng Han-chih is considered to be the godfather of the lucrative modern mango industry.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The traditional variety of mango, known as the “native mango” (土芒果), is smaller and more fibrous than modern varieties due to this they are often pickled or candied.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] 7* is a significant cash crop in Pingtung.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan is a significant producer of pineapples, with production primarily occurring in Pingtung and other southern regions.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Pineapples make up 40% of Taiwan's fruit exports by value.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2021 China banned the importation of pineapples from Taiwan just as the season was beginning claiming that previous imports had been contaminated with pests, claims questioned or denied by experts, producers, and the Taiwanese government.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In response to the ban the Taiwanese government asked the Taiwanese people and diplomatic allies to increase their consumption of Taiwan's “Freedom Pineapples” and promised financial assistance to any farmers who saw losses as a result of the ban.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The “Freedom Pineapples” initiative received support from allies such as Canada and the United States with the Canadians referencing the Canadian invention pineapple pizza.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The Freedom Pineapple campaign was launched by Foreign Minister Joseph Wu on Twitter.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Lychee production is significant with more than 3,000 hectares under cultivation in Kaohsiung alone.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The two main varieties are Heiyezi and Yuhebao.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Production was reduced in 2021 due to drought.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Independent winemaking was illegal in Taiwan for a long time due to the monopoly granted to the Taiwan Tobacco and Liquor Corporation.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan Tobacco and Liquor Corporation produced just one wine, a rosé.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] With liberalization following the end of military rule independent winemakers became legal in 2002 and in 2014 a Taiwanese wine won its first gold medal at an international competition.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The primary grapes cultivated for winemaking in Taiwan are Black Queen and Golden Muscat which were both introduced to the country in the 1950s.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] A red wine from Taichung was awarded a gold medal at the 25th Vinalies Internationales in France.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2020 Taiwanese wines won two gold medals at the 26th Vinalies Internationales Competition.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Grape harvest in Taiwan is dictated by the typhoon season which means growers are sometimes forced to pick less than ripe fruit.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Two of the most acclaimed wineries are Domaine Shu Sheng and Weightstone Vineyard Estate & Winery.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The relative rarity and high quality of Taiwanese wines makes them particularly prized by Hong Kong collectors.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Although it was once largely lost Taiwan's indigenous winemaking culture is staging a comeback.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Wax apples are a significant crop in Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwanese researchers have bred firmer, larger, and more deeply red varieties of the wax apple to appeal to the local market and growing conditions.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] This has led some to inaccurately believe that wax apples themselves were invented in Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The variety *Black Pearl* is highly valued.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Production of wax apples in concentrated in Taitung County, Kaohsiung, and Pingtung County.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Annual production is 47,000 metric tons.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Historically, 10% of production was exported to China, but Chinese authorities banned new imports of Taiwanese wax apples in 2021.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Pingtung's southern coast is particularly productive for wax apples as the trees perform favorably in slightly saline conditions.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Indian jujube production in Taiwan is significant.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Productions is centered in Kaohsiung with 750 hectares, 40% of the national total, of Indian jujubes.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Persimmon growing in Taiwan peaked at 5,300 hectares but declined to 4,700 hectares by 2024 largely due to the impacts of typhoons and climate change on production.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Most Taiwanese persimmons are consumed domestically with dried persimmons especially favored.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The most commonly cultivated strawberry variety in Taiwan is the *Taoyuan No.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Wild mushrooms and fungus were widely consumed by the indigenous people of Taiwan as well as being used for medicinal and spiritual purposes.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Commercial mushroom farming on Taiwan can be traced to methods introduced during the Japanese period.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The industry took off in the 1950s after being targeted by the U.S.-ROC Joint Commission on Rural Reconstruction (JCRR) for development.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Exports of canned mushrooms began in 1960 and by 1963 Taiwan was the world's top mushroom exporter with a third of the global market.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Exports of canned mushrooms peaked in 1978 before declining as production shifted to lower cost countries.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Today the vast majority of mushrooms produced on Taiwan are consumed locally but due to high mushroom consumption the industry is very large.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Mushrooms account for 18% of the value of Taiwan's non-meat food production.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] New farming methods and localized marketing have allowed traditional producers to remain competitive with large industrialized producers.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2013, Taiwan harvested 2.75 million tonnes of vegetables from 1,460 km2 of land with a total value of US$170 million.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Major vegetables cultivated include broccoli, cabbage, carrot, chayote, Chinese cabbage, edamame, eggplant, kai-lan, onion, scallion and spinach.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Vegetable plantation areas are mostly located in central and southern Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The peak harvest time is during the autumn and winter seasons.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Vegetable production is increasingly the focus of urban agriculture including vertical farming due to the desire to maximize crop yield from relatively small plots without using excessive amounts of pesticides or fertilizers.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Increased production is also driven by a desire to minimize Taiwanese dependence on other countries as sources of fresh produce, especially high value vegetables.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan's vertical vegetable farms are some of the most advanced in the world.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taoyuan's iFarm was Asia's largest vertical farm when it opened in 2018.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Sweet potatoes have been grown in Taiwan since at least 1603 following their introduction to Asian by the Spanish.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] However the possibility exists that the sweet potato reached Taiwan before the Spanish colonization of the new world.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] It rapidly became a staple of local diets.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Poor families would often mix sweet potato into their rice or millet to stretch it out.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Unlike the other staples of rice and millet, sweet potatoes could be grown on hillsides with limited preparation.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Cultivation of sweet potato reached its height during the Japanese colonial period with Taiwan ranking fourth in output from 1934 to 1938 after China, Japan, and the United States with 3.7% of world production.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Production fell as a result of World War II and economic disruption.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] It took off again in the 1950s and 1960s but with most of the crop destined to feed hogs not people.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Production fell again after commercial swine producers switched to imported grains like corn for their feed.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In modern Taiwan sweet potatoes are grown as a root vegetable, as a leaf vegetable, and for their starch.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] 40% of the crop is exported to Singapore and Hong Kong with the rest being consumed domestically either fresh or processed.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Sweet potatoes are associated with poverty and their consumption is avoided by many elders however sweet potatoes continue to play an important part in Taiwanese cuisine.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Research into the sweet potato at the Chiayi research station of the Taiwan Agricultural Research institute began in 1922.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] For the first 20 years after its founding in 1971 the World Vegetable Center was a major global sweet potato research center with over 1,600 ascensions in their first two years of operation.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 1991 the World Vegetable Center chose to end its sweet potato research due to high costs and other institutions with a tighter focus coming into existence.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The WVC duplicated and transferred its research and germplasm to the International Potato Center and Taiwan Agricultural Research institute.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The counties of Yunlin, Taichung, Miaoli and Changhwa are the main sweet potato producers.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Hualien county is known for its unique varieties of sweet potato.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2013, Taiwan harvested about 15,000 tons of tea with a total value of NT$6.92 billion, of which 3,919 tons was exported.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan's tea produces are oolong tea, pouchong tea, green tea and black tea.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan began cultivating tea around two hundred years ago.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2013, Taiwan harvested flowers with a total value of NT$16.52 billion, in which US$189.7 million of it was exported.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Flower plantation land spreads over an area of 138 km2.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Chrysanthemum floriculture takes the most land share among other types of flowers.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan is the world's largest exporter of orchids, which represented 87% of the flower export value in 2013.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The main export markets for Taiwanese flowers are the United States, Japan and the Netherlands.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The export oriented flower market suffered during the COVID-19 pandemic with an increase in domestic consumption and government support necessary to keep the industry profitable.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The Taipei Flower Market is the largest plant and flower market in Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The Taiwan Floriculture Development Association is the primary industry association.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2013, Taiwan produced livestock and poultry with a total value of NT$150 billion.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan's major livestock are pigs, and the major poultry is chickens, both as broilers and eggs.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan exported 10,890 tons of animal products and imported 295,063 tons.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] 90% of pork consumed in Taiwan is domestically produced.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The Giant African snail was introduced to Taiwan by the Japanese in 1932 and have since formed a significant part of rural food culture.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Only since the advent of commercial farming of the white-jade variety in the 1980s has consumption become widespread.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan is a significant goat producer but produces few sheep, the mandarin for both species is yang (羊) which leads to little distinction between them in cuisine.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Most local meat sold as mutton in Taiwan is in fact goat.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Pork production peaked in the years before 1997 when foot-and-mouth disease arrived in Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In those years Taiwan was the second largest exporter of pork after Denmark.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The traditional method of feeding pigs with food scraps has been restricted to the most advanced farms due to concerns about African swine fever.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2020 three quarters of Taiwan's pork farmers produced less than 1000 pigs a year.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Chicken and egg producers have had a hard time scaling to meet demand because of issues with disposing of large amounts of waste products.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2022 daily egg consumption was 24 million and local production was 22.6 million.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Geese are a significant part of Taiwan's livestock and cuisine.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Turkeys have been raised in Taiwan since partial Dutch colonization, production increased in the 1950s due to demand from US soldiers newly stationed in Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Turkey production remained significant after the drawdown in US forces.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Aquaculture has a long history in Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] By 2006 the production of Taiwanese coastal aquaculture was valued at NT$11,817 million.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In the 21st century high technology is playing a greater part in Taiwan's aquaculture industry as the industry struggles to cope with labor shortages and fierce foreign competition.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The Taiwanese government operates six fisheries and aquaculture research centers.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The Aquaculture Taiwan Expo & Forum is the primary aquaculture trade show in Taiwan, it is held concurrently with the Livestock Taiwan Expo & Forum and the Asia Agri-Tech Expo & Forum.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan is one of the largest fishing nations on earth and the associated fish processing industry is also significant.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] More than one third of the worlds longline tuna fishing vessels are operated by Taiwanese companies with the total strength of the distant waters fishing fleet at more than 2,000 vessels.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The fishing industry is estimated to be worth approximately two billion dollars.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan's ocean fisheries sector employs 350,000 people and there are 130,000 fishing households in Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2023, agriculture accounted for 1.51% of Taiwan's gross domestic product (GDP) with a total value of NT$351 billion.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan exports around US$5 billion worth of agricultural products annually.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Major overseas markets include Canada, Mainland China, Japan, the Republic of Korea, Thailand, Vietnam and the United States.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The agriculture sector employs around 500,000 people in Taiwan, about 4.4% of the total population.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2022, there were around 760,000 farm households.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] There are 1.1 hectares of cultivatable land per farm family.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan's agricultural financing system consists of the Agricultural Bank of Taiwan (Chinese: 全國農業金庫) and credit departments of farmers' and fishermen's associations, which fall under the supervision of the Agricultural Finance Agency (Chinese: 農業金融署) of the MOA.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The Agricultural Credit Guarantee Fund (Chinese: 農業信用保證基金) is responsible for financing farmers without enough collateral to acquire working capital.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan has a number of agricultural organizations that provide assistance to farmers, such as supply, distribution, and financial services.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] These include 302 farmers' associations, 40 fishermen's associations and 3,490 irrigation groups.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan had one agrarian political party, the Taiwan Farmers' Party, established on 15 June 2007.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] However, the party was disbanded on 3 October 2019.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] There are 16 research institutes established under the COA aimed to the development and innovation of technologies in agriculture-related produce.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2023, the Taiwan Agricultural Research Institute made 67 agricultural technology transfers to the private sector, earning NT$7.1 million in licensing fee and around NT$500,000 in royalties.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Spatial planning for agricultural farms in Taiwan is embedded into the Taiwan Agriculture Land Information Service (Chinese: 臺灣農地資訊服務網) whose data is collected by Formosat-2 earth observation satellite.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Information of farmland availability, soil properties, cropping suitability, irrigation infrastructures, land use zoning, and land consolidation are available for public access.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2020, the food self-sufficiency of Taiwan was 35%.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] President Tsai Ing-wen has stated that she hopes Taiwan's food self-sufficiency can be raised to 40% in the near term.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] As of 2021 the nation's rice reserves were large enough to feed the country for 18 months with fruit and vegetable reserves of six months.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2014, agriculture sector consumed a total 2,832.9 GWh of electricity.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Between 2000 and 2009, annual agricultural sector in Taiwan consumed 15.81 billion tons of water.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Over the past few years, agritourism has become more and more popular in Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The government has built recreational areas around farms and fishing villages by integrating the produce, nature and festivals.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2013, there are more than 75 recreation farming zones have been established and there are almost 317 recreational farms have been licensed.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Food-related museums are also plenty in Taiwan.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Agritourism forms a significant part of the total revenue for the agricultural industry.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Many small family farms rely on tourism as their primary means of earning an income.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Leisure farms, farm tours, farm stays, and other tourism related activities are popular both with domestic Taiwanese travelers and with international ones.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The Taiwanese Agritourism industry has received significant state support.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2018 TreeHugger ranked Taiwan the #1 agritourism destination in the world.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Fruit tourism is a subsection of agritourism with fruit picking being the prime attraction.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Taiwan's diverse subtropical climate means that there is always some sort of fruit in season.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Fruit tourism is popular with both domestic and international tourists.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] The region of Pingtung in particular is a fruit tourism destination.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] Erjie Rice Barn, Flying Cow Ranch, Fushoushan Farm, Fuxing Barn, Jingzaijiao Tile-paved Salt Fields, Qingjing Farm, Rareseed Ranch, Shangri-La Leisure Farm, Shanlong Vegetable Park, Toucheng Leisure Farm, Tsou Ma Lai Farm and Wuling Farm.
[src:bakkwa/agriculture-in-taiwan] In 2021 as a result of the tourism downturn due to the COVID-19 pandemic the Council of Agriculture announced subsidies for leisure farms.
[src:bakkwa/ais-kacang] Traditionally, an ice shaving machine is used to churn out the shaved ice used in the dessert, originally hand cranked but now more often motorised.
[src:bakkwa/ais-kacang] Many Southeast Asian coffee shops, hawker centres and food courts sell this dessert.
[src:bakkwa/ais-kacang] Early versions of ais kacang was first known to have been prepared around the time before and after the First World War, where the costs of ice manufacturing was becoming more affordable.
[src:bakkwa/ais-kacang] An earlier variant of the Singaporean dish was described as green, made from shaved ice, paired with syrups, *soaked seeds* and seaweed jelly and was sold mainly by street vendors.
[src:bakkwa/ais-kacang] The dish underwent many different alterations and variants throughout the history of Singapore, where during the 1920s, one version of it was described as shaved ice topped with rose water, lime or liquorice.
[src:bakkwa/ais-kacang] A version of the dish, known as Kachang mera, was also sold during the 1930s.
[src:bakkwa/ais-kacang] By the 1940s, the version of the dish described as having "shaved ice heaped into a little mountain", topped with red beans, "a Chinese grape-like fruit", syrup, and condensed or evaporated milk, similar to how it is being prepared today, began to appear.
[src:bakkwa/ais-kacang] Some earlier variants of ais kacang are no longer sold, such as the ice ball version of the dessert, which was popular during the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:bakkwa/ais-kacang] In Malaysia, variants now contain a large serving of *attap chee* (palm seed), red beans, sweet corn, grass jelly, roasted peanuts, and cubes of agar agar as common ingredients.
[src:bakkwa/ais-kacang] Other less common ingredients include aloe vera, *cendol*, *nata de coco*, and ice cream.
[src:bakkwa/ais-kacang] A final topping of evaporated milk, condensed milk, or coconut milk is drizzled over the mountain of ice along with red rose syrup and sarsi syrup.
[src:bakkwa/ais-kacang] Some stalls have even introduced novelty toppings such as durian and chocolate syrup.
[src:bakkwa/ais-kacang] There are also versions that shun the multi-coloured syrup and are served instead with just a drizzling of palm sugar syrup.
[src:bakkwa/ais-kacang] In Singapore, traditional ice kachang is usually made from shaved ice, packed into a mountain-like shape and consists of red beans, creamed corn, attap chee, cendol, and grass jelly, similar to the Malaysian version, and drizzled with syrups made from gula melaka, red rose syrup, and pandan syrup.
[src:bakkwa/ais-kacang] The dish has evolved to include fruits such as durian, mango, toppings such as Milo, peanuts, and sago pearls among others.
[src:bakkwa/bakkwa] Bakkwa is made with a meat preservation and preparation technique originating from China.
[src:bakkwa/bakkwa] The general method of production has remained virtually unchanged throughout the centuries, but the techniques have been gradually improved.
[src:bakkwa/bakkwa] It is traditionally made of pork, beef, or mutton, which is prepared with spices, sugar, salt and soy sauce, then dried on racks at around 50 to 60 °C (122 to 140 °F) to a final water activity between 0.60 and 0.69.
[src:bakkwa/bakkwa] Nowadays, products with a softer texture, lighter color and less sugar are preferred.
[src:bakkwa/bakkwa] The *shafu* type of bakkwa products has a higher water content, and thus has a softer texture and lower sugar content.
[src:bakkwa/bakkwa] Whereas the traditional bakkwa has a water activity below 0.7, *shafu* bakkwa tends to be closer to a water activity of about 0.79.
[src:bakkwa/bakkwa] Nevertheless, *shafu* can have a similar shelf life to other types of bakkwa.
[src:bakkwa/bakkwa] Bakkwa is very popular in Singapore and Malaysia where it is traditionally eaten during the Chinese New Year.
[src:bakkwa/bakkwa] When Chinese immigrants brought this delicacy over to Singapore and Malaysia, it began to take on local characteristics.
[src:bakkwa/bakkwa] A notable example lies in the preparation of bakkwa, where the meat is grilled over charcoal rather than air-dried, imparting a smokier flavor to the meat.
[src:bakkwa/bakkwa] The Singaporean and Malaysian versions of bakkwa are also sweeter than their mainland China counterparts with many different variations having developed to suit local palates, such as chili bakkwa.
